I've read the full draft. This piece has already been through fresh-eyes and second-pass review, and it shows. Here's the cohesion audit.

## Cohesion Audit: jim-carrey.md

### Central Thesis
Jim Carrey is a Type 7 whose engine is escape from pain rather than the pursuit of joy, and his late-period "I don't exist" turn is not a breakdown but the first time a man who spent fifty years running finally stopped.

### Thread Map

| Section | Contributes | Connects because |
|---|---|---|
| **Intro** (check → red carpet diptych) | Sets thesis: the most alive performer announced he wanted to disappear | Plants "a Seven reaching the end of the road he was running down" |
| **What Is His Personality Type?** | Diagnosis: a 7 flees pain, doesn't chase fun | Pays off the intro's "Seven"; ends teasing "a tire factory, a tent, and a father" |
| **Grew Up Performing in a Van** | Origin: performing to make pain *leave* (sick room + factory) | Delivers the tire factory/tent the prior section teased |
| **The $10M Check** | Ambition as Seven psychology; victory and wound in one casket | The childhood "so run" finds its first big expression |
| **Turned Escape Into a Career** | Comedy as the escape vehicle; the Truman/Kaufman/Eternal Sunshine trio | The mountain-top let-down pivots to *how* he ran |
| **Says He Doesn't Exist** | The turn; depression-as-more; the White grief test | Trio ends "on a red carpet" → this IS that red carpet |
| **Rabbit Hole** | Optional wing/subtype/arrows aside | Quarantined; main thread survives skipping it |
| **What He Sounds Like When He Stops Running** | "I have enough" x3 = foot off the gas | Shares the exact pull-quote that closed the prior section |
| **The Last Trick of an Escape Artist** | Un-retirement irony; keeps one foot on the gas | Complicates the stillness the prior section reached |

Read top to bottom, that outline holds as a coherent argument. That is the test passing.

